# templates/drivers/herdr-claude.driver — the DEFAULT (and only shipped) driver:
#   multiplexer = herdr · agent runtime = Claude Code.
#
# A "driver" binds each runtime-specific coordinator capability to a concrete command incantation.
# render_skill() (bin/herd) sources the driver selected by the HERD_DRIVER config key
# (default: herdr-claude) and substitutes each {{DRIVER_*}} token in templates/coordinator.md.tmpl
# with the value below — the SAME {{TOKEN}} machinery that fills {{WORKSPACE_NAME}}, {{SCRIPTS_DIR}},
# {{CAPABILITIES}}, … See docs/driver-abstraction.md for the capability model + phase-2 design.
#
# CONTRACT (mirrors .herd/config): shell-sourceable KEY=value, COMMITTED, ZERO-SECRET — command
# SHAPES only, never credentials. With HERD_DRIVER unset/default the rendered coordinator skill is
# FUNCTIONALLY IDENTICAL to before this abstraction existed (the render-equivalence test is the rail).
# A different runtime ships its own <name>.driver binding these same keys to its control surface;
# a driver missing a key the template tokenizes fails the render loudly (an unrendered {{DRIVER_*}}).

# ── Capabilities the coordinator skill binds INLINE (greppable as DRIVER:<cap> in the skill) ──────
DRIVER_LIST_AGENTS='herdr agent list'
DRIVER_FOCUS_AGENT='herdr agent focus <slug>'
DRIVER_SEND_TEXT='herdr pane run <agent-pane> "<text>"'
DRIVER_SWITCH_MODEL='herdr pane run <builder-agent-pane> "/model <MODEL_FEATURE value>"'

# ── Capabilities the LANE SCRIPTS + watcher exercise (not inline skill text) — bound here so a
#    phase-2 driver covers the FULL runtime surface, not just the four the skill names inline. ──────
DRIVER_START_AGENT='bash {{SCRIPTS_DIR}}/herd-feature.sh <slug> "<task>"'
DRIVER_CREATE_TAB='herdr tab create --workspace <ws>'
DRIVER_READ_PANE='herdr pane read <pane>'
DRIVER_SEND_KEYS='herdr pane send-keys <pane> <keys>'
